<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO TAO</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun 23  6:25:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tao,<br><br>
I thank you for your message.<br><br>
The impression I had of the peasants in Vietnam is that their greatest desire was to be left alone to grow their rice.<br><br>
Instead they were subjected to years of war.<br><br>
I agree with you that communism is evil. Yet in relation to the government of Ngo Dinh Diem, just how evil was it? A very strong argument can be made that Diem represented a  powerful and small faction of privileged cronies at the expense of the aforementioned peasants.<br><br>
Rather than address Ho Chi Minh's overtures at Versailles or after WWII, the US chose to support French colonialism.<br><br>
It didn't matter that Diem's government didn't address land reform in the south, just so long as he was doing our bidding. Diem was only one of the &quot;strongmen&quot; we propped up in our zeal to contain world wide communism. We failed to see Ho's struggle as being one of nationalism - even though his complaints were similar to those that Americans had during the time of their own revolution.<br><br>
My intention is not to paint a rosy picture of communism. But, what does the image of Buddhist monks immolating themselves say about the Diem government? <br><br>
The faction we supported (the Diem family) was no more representative of the people of Vietnam than the communists were/are. Ask the peasants who suffered the brunt of the war.<br><br>
It was not our fight.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


